teenth-century quest for future certainty had an especially ironic consequence: it led Americans to accept uncertainty as an inescapable part of both forecasting and twentieth-century economic and cultural life. Drawing together histories of science, technology, capitalism, environment, and culture, Looking Forward explores how forecasts functioned as new forms of knowledge and risk management tools that sometimes mitigated, but at other times exacerbated, the very uncertainties they were designed to conquer. Ultimately Pietruska shows how Americans came to understand the future itself as predictable, yet still uncertain.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEconomic forecastingzUnited States. 0aForecastingxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aProphecy. 0aRiskzUnited States. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  acrop forecasting.  aeconomic forecasting.  aforecasting.  afortune-telling.  afuture.  aknowledge production.  aprediction.  arisk management.  auncertainty.  aweather forecasting.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017z978311071193640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226509150423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226509150/original  a978-3-11-071193-6  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2017b2017  aGBV-deGruyter-alles